        // and toggles the "show past items" visibility rule.
        // Called on startup and whenever settings change.
```

#### 12. **ACTIONS SECTION** (Lines 859-887 in V1)
**Location to insert**: Before `const Actions = {` (current file line 822)
```
        // ─── ACTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        // The ONLY place in the app that modifies State.
        // Every user gesture eventually calls an Action method, never mutating State directly.
        // This single-write-path makes it easy to reason about what can change and when.
        //
        // Pattern: most methods call this.mutate(fn, event, payload)
        //   fn      — a function that performs the actual State mutation
        //   event   — the EventBus event name that Render listens to
        //   payload — optional data passed to the Render handler (e.g. which date changed)
```

#### 13. **RENDER SECTION** (Lines 1238-1246 in V1)
**Location to insert**: Before `const Render = {` (current file line 1122)
```
        // ─── RENDER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        // The visual rendering layer. Entirely derived from State — never mutates it.
        // On each event from the EventBus (e.g. 'itemsChanged'), Render updates the DOM
        // to match the new State. Render only reads State, never writes it.
        //
        // Key methods:
        //   hardRebuild()      — destroys and recreates entire journal DOM
        //   trackContent(d)    — patches just the lane cells for one date
        //   header()           — renders the sticky column headers
        //   horizonData()      — renders the filtered "important items" panel
        //   updateProgress()   — updates the task-completion progress bars
        //   applyScrollFilter() — shows/hides Horizon entries based on scroll position
```

#### 14. **VIRTUAL SCROLL SECTION** (Lines 1350-1360 in V1)
**Location to insert**: Before `const VirtualScroll = {` (current file line 1798)
```
        // ─── VIRTUAL SCROLL ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        // Efficiently renders a 120-day window at a time, swapping days in and out as
        // the user scrolls. Uses an IntersectionObserver to detect when sentinels become
        // visible, triggering batch loads. Once a batch is complete, old days at the
        // opposite end are quietly removed from the DOM to keep memory bounded.
        //
        // This design lets the app handle months of history smoothly without bloating
        // the DOM or requiring a virtual list library.
```

#### 15. **DRAG-DROP SECTION** (Lines 1415-1429 in V1)
**Location to insert**: Before `const DragDrop = {` (current file line 1890)
```
        // ─── DRAG-DROP ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        // Enables reordering and moving tasks between lanes/days using SortableJS library.
        // Every .track element (the lane cell for a day) gets a Sortable instance that
        // allows items to be dragged within the track, cloned to another track, or dropped
        // into the overdue-bin (which acts as a read-only clone source).
        //
        // Cloning is critical: when you drag a task from its source lane, SortableJS doesn't
        // move it — it clones it. This keeps the task in the source lane until the onEnd
        // handler explicitly calls Actions.reorderTrack() to change State (which re-renders
        // is already being appended to the DOM.
```

